Transition committee chairman, Ikwuano local government council, Deacon Steve Ojigbo has said that the agricultural potentials of the area are limitless, assuring of the council’s desire to harness them. Ojigbo stated this while speaking to LEADERSHIP Friday in his office at the council headquarters, Isiala Oboro, inviting enterprenuers from across the country to come and invest in them. He said the area is richly blessed in the production of both food and cash crops, noting however, that most of them are lost due to inadequate post harvest management and other challenges. Ojigbo, who lauded the present administration in the state for its agricultural policies and programmes, appealed to the youth to key into the sector to create employments for themselves and others. Regretting that the sector has been overlooked by the youth and the society in general for a long time, the council boss stressed that every effort should be put in place to return it to its former position. “It is an incontrovertible fact that until the oil boom era, agriculture was the mainstay of the country. The economy was stronger than what it is now, there was food security, and low unemployment. He expressed concern over the deplorable condition of the Umuahia-Ikot Ekpene road which passes across the state, stressing that the ongoing rehabilitation of the road appears to be sluggish. “This is part of the challenges I said earlier. Governments at all levels in the county should provide quality infrastructure such as roads, electricity, and health care services to make life easy for the people. The onetime commissioner in the state warned the youth against allowing themselves to be used by “disgruntled politicians to cause crisis while their own children are in their comfort zones.” Ojigbo, who recently announced the appointment 61 community youth presidents in the area as his aides on his payroll, added that he is appreciative of the level of security of lives and property in the area. 